Teaching
Courses
___________________Rowan University___________________
Intro. to Health and Science Comm.: Students are introduced to the ways in which people communicate about
health and illness, environmental risk, and science policy. This is the
required introductory course for the program in Health and Science
Communication (HSC). The course is open to non-majors.
Spring 2022; Fall 2021; Spring 2021; Fall 2020
Comprehending COVID-19: Comprehending COVID-19 provides you the opportunity to learn from
Rowan University faculty who are directly and indirectly studying this
pandemic. Faculty are drawn from multiple areas to bring a complex,
reasoned look at the current and future implications of COVID-19.
Lead instructor. Course developed collaboratively with 14 Rowan
University faculty, representing 10 different departments across campus.
Spring 2021; Fall 2020; Summer 2020
Write Up: https://news.yahoo.com/rowan-university-course-explores-
impact-163311537.html
Seminar in Communication Studies: This writing intensive course provides a seminar experience in areas of
communication that are not part of the regular course offerings. Examples
of potential topics include Friendship, Rhetoric of Music, Romantic
Relationships, and Presidential Campaigns. Theme: New Media Rhetorics;
Summer 2023; Fall 2022; Summer 2022; Spring 2020
Public Speaking: This course trains students in the fundamentals of public speaking,
including study and practice of speech preparation and speech delivery.
The goal is to enable the student to participate effectively in oral
communication, as a student, professionally and as a citizen.
Winter 2022; Winter 2020
Rhetoric of Sci., Tech., & Med.: Students are introduced to key thinkers and theories in the area of
rhetoric of science, technology, and medicine (RSTM). Students marshal
their learning to study a chosen RSTM topic/problem and create messaging
to solve that problem. Identity and ideology in scientific, technological, and
medical discourses are highlighted throughout.
Fall 2023; Spring 2022; Fall 2019
Rhetorical Criticism: This course surveys ancient to modern theories of speech criticism to
develop defensible criteria for evaluating speeches, social movements, and
non-oratorical events. Students study and evaluate past and present public
speeches by applying various rhetorical standards.
Fall 2023; Spring 2023; Fall 2022; Spring 2022; Fall 2021;
Summer 2021; Spring 2021; Fall 2020; Spring 2020; Fall 2019
___________________Seattle University___________________

Other/Creative Work
ByrdBota dynamic web application, written in JavaScript, which sources bird songs from the
Cornell Lab of Ornithologys archives to sonically represent differences in anthropogenic
species displacement in New Jersey between 1970 and 2017 and 2065. The project was
developed in collaboration with Dr. Charles Schutte (Environmental Science, Rowan
University) as well as undergraduate students from Communication Studies and
Environmental Science. Physical installations of ByrdBot were placed in the Chamberlain
Student Center, Bozorth Hall, and Science Hall at Rowan University, February 2023-Present.
Project URL: https://soundsofhumanimpact.github.io/byrdbot/
Write Ups: https://today.rowan.edu/news/2022/06/they-call-it-the-byrd-bot.-
listen-to-it-tweet..html
https://www.scicommbites.org/post/byrdbot-simulated-tweets-to-
communicate-climate-change
feels_botan interactive exhibit constructed from JavaScript that utilizes artificial intelligence,
crowdsourced .gifs, and custom-designed sounds to catch feels from users (e.g., to identify and
respond to emotions detected from users). Physically installed as part of the Pull Request art
exhibition in the Vachon Gallery at Seattle University, September-October 2018.
Write Up: https://www.seattleu.edu/artsci/about/news/pull-request-collaborative-
code-art.html
